SIMPLE: mountaineer
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Mountaineer
<hw>Moun`tain*eer"</hw> <pr>(moun`t⟦icr⟧n*⟦emac⟧r")</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>
<ety>[OF. <ets>montanier</ets>, LL. <ets>montanarius</ets>. See
<er>Mountain</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>An inhabitant of a mountain;
one who lives among mountains.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A rude, fierce person.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>No savage fierce, bandit, or <qex>mountaineer</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A person who climbs mountains for sport.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mountaineer</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: mountaineer
<hw>moun`tain*eer"</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To live or act as a
mountaineer; to climb mountains.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>You can't go <qex>mountaineering</qex> in a flat country.</q>
<rj><qau>H. James.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mountaineering</ent>⟦br⟧
